
Task: Enable SSL/TLS on AWS Load Balancers

⸻

A. Steps to Enable SSL/TLS on an Application Load Balancer (ALB)
	1.	Open the EC2 Console
	•	Go to Load Balancers
	•	Select your Application Load Balancer
	2.	Add a Listener
	•	Click Listeners → Add listener
	•	Protocol: HTTPS
	•	Port: 443
	3.	Configure Listener Action
	•	Action: Forward
	•	Select the appropriate Target Group
	4.	Configure SSL Settings
	•	Choose an SSL Security Policy
	•	Leave default unless older TLS/SSL compatibility is required
	5.	Select SSL Certificate
	•	Choose one of the following:
	•	ACM (Amazon Certificate Manager) – recommended
	•	IAM – not recommended
	•	Import certificate (paste private key, certificate body, and chain)
	6.	Save the Listener
	•	Review settings and create/update the listener

⸻

B. Steps to Enable SSL/TLS on a Network Load Balancer (NLB)
	1.	Open the EC2 Console
	•	Go to Load Balancers
	•	Select your Network Load Balancer
	2.	Add a Listener
	•	Click Listeners → Add listener
	•	Protocol: TLS
	•	Port: 443
	3.	Configure Listener Action
	•	Action: Forward
	•	Select the appropriate Target Group
	4.	Configure Security Policy
	•	Choose a TLS security policy
	•	Use the default unless specific compliance is required
	5.	Select SSL Certificate
	•	Choose one of the following:
	•	ACM
	•	IAM
	•	Import certificate
	6.	(Optional) Configure ALPN
	•	Application Layer Protocol Negotiation
	•	Advanced setting (can be skipped)
	7.	Save the Listener
	•	Review and create/update the listener

That is how to enable SSL/TLS on AWS load balancers 
